This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with the problem of RGB-D semantic segmentation of indoor images. It also involves the use of convolutional and deconvolutional networks, which are commonly used in computer vision tasks. 

The paper also involves the development of a new structure for deconvolution of multiple modalities, which suggests that it may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. 

Additionally, the paper proposes a novel feature transformation network, which involves discovering common and specific features between the two modalities. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. 

The use of deconvolutional networks also suggests that the paper may belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category. 

Finally, the paper involves the segmentation of images, which suggests that it may also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
